From: pn002b@uhura.cc.rochester.edu (Peter C. Norton)
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: Mon, 30 Aug 93 04:30:38 GMT

In <25r4of$aov@samba.oit.unc.edu> ses@tipper.oit.unc.edu (Simon E Spero) writes:

>To set matters straight; _NT_ is a multi-user operating system in that NT 
>allows for multiple processes to be run by different owning users at the 
>same time. Access to shared resources such as files can be controlled through
>the use of ACLS.

No one is saying that it can't support multiple *users*.  DOS can do that.
But can it support them at the same time?  Can I use something analagous
to SLIP to log in to my work machine from home, and use my programs and read
my mail and send and recieve files while an administrator checks users' 
passwords for security and another user ping's a computer at a remote site?
That is multi-user.  The multi-user that you are describing can be achieved
under DOS with a security program like ironclad.

>NT 3.1 does not provide any applications to allow a remote user to 'login' 
>and execute arbritrary programs. In addition, there is no documented API
>for obtaining a token to allow a process to act as a different user (setuid
>and friends). mail complaints to postmaster@FTC.gov

That is what makes something functionally multi-user.  So what is NT?
multi-tasking.  No-one is arguing that.  Well, not actually.  You don't
usually want a user to be able to execute an arbitrary program.  That's a
security risk.  But I guess that that's what straight BSD is, so it's just
a technicality.

---Peter

>In a nutshell, NT is a true multi-user  operating system, but at present
>there's no real way of making use of that fact apart from logging on and
>off. 
>-- 
>Hackers Local 42- National Union of Computer Operatives, Chapel Hill section
