From: drew@juliet.cs.colorado.edu (Drew Eckhardt)
Subject: Re: A nice linux story
Date: Mon, 30 Aug 1993 05:10:54 GMT

In article <xtifrCCHn6n.JLp@netcom.com> xtifr@netcom.com (Chris Waters) writes:
>In <CCIu07.3tw@royle.org> c@royle.org (Chris Royle) writes:
>
>
>>Absolutely - I quite agree, but they have never met such a converter before,
>>and are really very skeptical (note they, not me) about a free operating system
>>for which they do not pay for support and don't really know how to use.
>
>>I think they'd be happier if they paid for the lot of it and could ring up and
>>shout at someone if it went wrong. Then they'd trust the f2c, even though it's
>>the same - it's the backup and promise of reliability that they're after, and
>>they don't accept that they are getting that with free software.
>
>Well, there are plenty of people willing to sell service contracts for
>free software.  Have them talk to Cygnus!

Right now, Linux is a rapidly moving target, meaning few people are 
willing to support it.  Although in many installations, Linux has proved
more stable and given better performance than commercial systems like
SCO, there is too much broken Linux code (ie, networking) and too many
broken programs out there (ie, the gcc C++ frontend which generates
horribly incorrect code for some input on some platforms) for some one
to support the whole thing.   The wide variety of hardware that Linux
runs on also complicates things, especially with PC hardware which is 
often B.A.D (Broken As Designed, ie if everything breaks in the right
way it works).  I've personally traced a large number of bug reports 
to hardware problems with marginal hardware.

When the price is right, I support Linux for some subset of Linux
(ie, certain kernel revisions, certain device driver and hardware
combinations, certain user level programs) but at this point wouldn't 
be willing to support the whole thing for the reasons I outlined above.

