From: jim@n5ial.mythical.com (Jim Graham)
Subject: Re: High speed modems & Linux --- UUCP throughput
Date: Sun, 29 Aug 1993 23:11:54 GMT

In article <25ntjf$6rc@news.bu.edu> heiser@bumetb.bu.edu (Bill Heiser)
writes:
>In article <1993Aug29.071036.2740@jonh.wimsey.bc.ca>
>jhenders@jonh.wimsey.bc.ca (John Henders) writes:
>>
>>    UUCP is quite fast for me under linux. Here's the result of uurate
>>for the last 24 hours here. This is with a USR dual standard 14,400 

>>Remote  ------- Bytes -------- --- Time ---- -- Avg CPS -- -- Files --
>>Host      Rcvd    Sent   Total   Rcvd   Sent   Rcvd   Sent  Rcvd  Sent
>>-------- ------- ------- ------- ------ ------ ------ ----------- -----
>>van-bc      2.5M   63.6K 2597.1K  00:29  00:01 1444.6  851.5   134    80

One thing you need to be careful about---it's possible (probable) that
these stats include times for transferring the control files, and will
also probably include transfer of files that are really too small to be
of any value in a throughput measure.

It's better to look in your Stats file and look at incoming files that
are *AT LEAST* 200k (and if at all possible, twice that size).  Otherwise,
your measurements are, at best, uncertain.

>Have you done anything to customize your uucp configuration?  The
>best rate I've seen here so far is about 1100CPS, but on average it
>is much worse.

1100 cps for a V.32bis/V.42 connection, even with UUCP 'g', is pretty awful.
Btw, all throughput references I'm listing below are compressed news feeds,
V.32/V.42/V.42bis (even though V.42bis isn't doing much here) connections,
and I ignore any files that aren't big enough (at one point, there were a
bunch of nice huge files, around 400k each, from each site that I used for
throughput measurements).  Oh, serial port has 16550AFN, uses RTS/CTS flow
control, and is locked at 38.4 kb.  Oh yeah, one more thing....  Large
footprint USR Courier DS w/ square LEDs.

When connecting to my primary news feed and receiving news, I'm limited
to UUCP 'g' (he's currently running Waffle under dog, but that may change).
I get around 1350 cps on large files from him.

When connecting to the feed that I get col.* from (which, btw, is over a
long distance line), I'm using Taylor UUCP's 'j' protocol, and I see around
1650 cps, which is only about 74 cps below the approximate maximum for a
V.32bis/V.42 connection (assuming no improvement from V.42bis) after V.42's
async-to-sync conversion and protocol overhead are taken into account.
Considering that Zmodem (fully registered dog version) only yields around
1650 to 1700 cps, I'm not complaining too much.  :-)  I want those few extra
cps, but I'm not about to waste any time to get them!

Now, with that, I'd better get this posted before the approaching
thunderstorm (and the associated power failure for the island I live on)
arrive.....  :-)

Later,
   --jim

