From: henke@grumpy.ssc.gov (Douglas Henke)
Subject: Re: SLS considered harmful (wasRe: Bashing Peter MacDonald)
Date: Mon, 30 Aug 1993 07:01:35 GMT

>[Flames at and defense of SLS and Peter deleted for brevity]

Some people find SLS useful, others find it harmful. Welcome to the net. As
has been suggested (at length) by others, those who don't like it have
other options. For those of us who think that SLS, with all its attendant
warts, is of value, how about trying to do something productive about the
problems?

I suggest creating a list of problems with the current SLS, along with
proposed fixes. (I also suggest deliberately leaving out of such a list
things which amount to matters of personal taste. Thus "/dev/swap is a link
pointing to something which is probably not swap" would be included, while
"links should never go in /dev" would not.) This would not be the Linux
FAQ; it would be only for those problems specifically relating to SLS.

The point of the whole thing would be twofold: to help SLS fix the problems
in later releases, and to help users fix problems while they are waiting
for the next release.

Yeah, I guess this means I am volunteering to maintain the sucker. Anybody
interested? Send me mail with your comments or with problems you've found.
(I already know about /dev/swap, the missing /var/log, the kernel patch to
compile without quotas, and the missing /usr/spool/lpd. I'll write up some
detailed fixes for these, but if you have insights or that's-not-a-bug,
that's-a-feature arguments, I'd be happy to see 'em.)

If anybody seems to care, and even if they don't, I'll post later about how
to get copies of the most current list and where to send submissions. For
now, just mail to henke@scaly.ssc.gov.

                        -DGH "...or did somebody already do this?"

