Crossposted-To: comp.periphs.scsi,comp.sys.ibm.pc.hardware
From: drew@juliet.cs.colorado.edu (Drew Eckhardt)
Subject: Re: [Q] does the DTC 3270 Fast SCSI-2 controller work with Linux?
Date: Mon, 30 Aug 1993 06:31:32 GMT

In article <1993Aug27.223123.19083@grace.rt.cs.boeing.com> chrise@atc.boeing.com writes:
>Greetings-
>    I'm looking to buy a '486 from Comtrade (the EISA SCSI-2 VL-Bus system)
>and the disk controller that comes as standard is the DTC 3270. I want to run
>Linux on it, so I checked the SCSI portion of the most recent FAQ I could 
>find (July '93) and while it mentions that the Adaptec-compatible DTC 
>controllers DTC3290 and DTC3292 are supported, there is no explicit mention
>of the DTC3270 as either supported or not. Does anybody know if it is (or
>soon will be) supported under Linux or not?

No, and it won't be supported until DTC changes their corporate policy 
if what I've been told is accurate.

I got mail from a user interested in doing a DTC 3270 driver, and 
responded with pointers to the Linux SCSI driver manual and a suggestion
that Eric Youngdale and I were usually willing to answer technical 
questions concerning the Linux SCSI drivers.

A few days later, I got another mail from the user stating that 
he couldn't do the driver, because when he contacted DTC for hardware
documentation he was told

"We don't give out that type of information to the general public"

I've crossposted my reply to comp.periphs.scsi and comp.sys.ibm.pc.hardware,
in the hopes that someone in one of those groups has had a more positive 
experience dealing with DTC.

If this is the real corporate policy, and not what a frontline support 
person stated because he didn't know the real answer, users should 
consider buying their hardware from other companies that aren't outright 
hostile towards developers.
